{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4be1e989-95ef-4424-a073-a6ace91a5ca9","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2** / .NET 9. Here's the modern approach:\n\n### `TestContext` — use **constructor injection**\n\nThe old `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property pattern still works but constructor injection is preferred in v3:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        // Sync initialization goes here too\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### Async initialization — use `[TestInitialize]`\n\n`[TestInitialize]` supports `async Task`, so combine both:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private MyService _service;\n\n    // Constructor: sync init + TestContext injection\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n    }\n\n    // Async per-test init\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        _service = await MyService.CreateAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestCleanup]\n    public async Task CleanupAsync()\n    {\n        await _service.DisposeAsync();\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **Constructor** — sync init + `TestContext` injection (runs first)\n- **`[TestInitialize]`** — async init via `async Task` (runs before each test)\n- **`[ClassInitialize]`** — one-time static setup if needed (also supports `async Task`)","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1a07d0a8-1356-4297-b3e9-f277d2598a69","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. In MSTest v3, the recommended way to get `TestContext` is via constructor injection (not the property pattern). For initialization, you can use:\n\n1. Constructor for sync init\n2. `IAsyncInitialization` — actually, MSTest doesn't have that. Let me think again.\n\nIn MSTest v3, the patterns are:\n- **TestContext**: Inject via constructor (`public MyTests(TestContext testContext)`)\n- **Sync init**: Use `[TestInitialize]` or the constructor\n- **Async init**: Use `[TestInitialize]` with an `async Task` return type\n\n\n- **Class-level setup**: `[ClassInitialize]` for one-time initialization\n- **Per-test setup**: `[TestInitialize]` which supports both sync and async methods, or use the constructor for synchronous setup\n\nThe modern approach in MSTest 3.x is to inject `TestContext` through the constructor and use `[TestInitialize]` for any initialization logic, whether sync or async.","outputTokens":706,"requestId":"4821:2766CC:88BB14:9D11D5:69FBEB03"},"id":"63ad0013-83a4-4e49-b902-d1b583b79b4f","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:29:55.924Z","parentId":"6b4966f2-6f12-4618-baf7-6b8fbc8b8b68"}
